# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: disassembly-analysis
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] Assembly language usually has one statement per machine code instruction (1:1), but constants, comments, assembler directives, symbolic labels of, e.g., memory locations, registers, and macros are generally also supported.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] The first assembly code in which a language is used to represent machine code instructions is found in Kathleen and Andrew Donald Booth's 1947 work, *Coding for A.R.C.*.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] Assembly code is converted into executable machine code by a utility program referred to as an *assembler*.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] The term "assembler" is generally attributed to Wilkes, Wheeler and Gill in their 1951 book *The Preparation of Programs for an Electronic Digital Computer*, who, however, used the term to mean "a program that assembles another program consisting of several sections into a single program".
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] The conversion process is referred to as *assembly*, as in *assembling* the source code.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] The computational step when an assembler is processing a program is called *assembly time*.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] Because assembly depends on the machine code instructions, each assembly language is specific to a particular computer architecture such as x86 or ARM.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] Sometimes there is more than one assembler for the same architecture, and sometimes an assembler is specific to an operating system or to particular operating systems.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] Most assembly languages do not provide specific syntax for operating system calls, and most assembly languages can be used universally with any operating system, as the language provides access to all the real capabilities of the processor, upon which all system call mechanisms ultimately rest.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] In contrast to assembly languages, most high-level programming languages are generally portable across multiple architectures but require interpreting or compiling, much more complicated tasks than assembling.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] In the first decades of computing, it was commonplace for both systems programming and application programming to take place entirely in assembly language.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] While still irreplaceable for some purposes, the majority of programming is now conducted in higher-level interpreted and compiled languages.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] In "No Silver Bullet", Fred Brooks summarised the effects of the switch away from assembly language programming: "Surely the most powerful stroke for software productivity, reliability, and simplicity has been the progressive use of high-level languages for programming.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] Today, it is typical to use small amounts of assembly language code within larger systems implemented in a higher-level language, for performance reasons or to interact directly with hardware in ways unsupported by the higher-level language.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] For instance, just under 2% of version 4.9 of the Linux kernel source code is written in assembly; more than 97% is written in C.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] Assembly language uses mnemonic symbols to represent low-level machine instructions (opcodes), directives, and usually architectural registers and flags.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] Some of the mnemonics may be built-in and some user-defined.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] Many operations require one or more operands in order to form a complete instruction.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] Most assemblers permit named constants, registers, and labels for program and memory locations, and can calculate expressions for operands.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] Thus, programmers are freed from tedious repetitive calculations and assembler programs are much more readable than machine code.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] Depending on the architecture, these elements may also be combined for specific instructions or addressing modes using offsets or other data as well as fixed addresses.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] Many assemblers offer additional mechanisms to facilitate program development, to control the assembly process, and to aid debugging.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] Some are column oriented, with specific fields in specific columns; this was very common for machines using punched cards in the 1950s and early 1960s.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] Some assemblers have free-form syntax, with fields separated by delimiters, e.g., punctuation, white space.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] Some assemblers are hybrid, with, e.g., labels, in a specific column and other fields separated by delimiters; this became more common than column-oriented syntax in the 1960s.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] An **assembler** program creates object code by translating combinations of mnemonics and syntax for operations and addressing modes into their numerical equivalents.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] This representation typically includes an *operation code* ("opcode") as well as other control bits and data.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] The assembler also calculates constant expressions and resolves symbolic names for memory locations and other entities.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] The use of symbolic references is a key feature of assemblers, saving tedious calculations and manual address updates after program modifications.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] Most assemblers also include macro facilities for performing textual substitution – e.g., to generate common short sequences of instructions as inline, instead of *called* subroutines.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] Some assemblers may also be able to perform some simple types of instruction set-specific optimizations.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] One concrete example of this may be the ubiquitous x86 assemblers from various vendors.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] Called jump-sizing, most of them are able to perform jump-instruction replacements (long jumps replaced by short or relative jumps) in any number of passes, on request.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] Others may even do simple rearrangement or insertion of instructions, such as some assemblers for RISC architectures that can help optimize a sensible instruction scheduling to exploit the CPU pipeline as efficiently as possible.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] Assemblers have been available since the 1950s, as the first step above machine language and before high-level programming languages such as Fortran, Algol, COBOL and Lisp.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] There have also been several classes of translators and semi-automatic code generators with properties similar to both assembly and high-level languages, with Speedcode as perhaps one of the better-known examples.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] There may be several assemblers with different syntax for a particular CPU or instruction set architecture.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] For instance, an instruction to add memory data to a register in a x86-family processor might be `add eax,[ebx]`, in original *Intel syntax*, whereas this would be written `addl (%ebx),%eax` in the *AT&T syntax* used by the GNU Assembler.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] Despite different appearances, different syntactic forms generally generate the same numeric machine code.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] A single assembler may also have different modes in order to support variations in syntactic forms as well as their exact semantic interpretations (such as FASM-syntax, TASM-syntax, ideal mode, etc., in the special case of x86 assembly programming).
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] There are two types of assemblers based on how many passes through the source are needed (how many times the assembler reads the source) to produce the object file.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] In both cases, the assembler must be able to determine the size of each instruction on the initial passes in order to calculate the addresses of subsequent symbols.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] In an assembler with peephole optimization, addresses may be recalculated between passes to allow replacing pessimistic code with code tailored to the exact distance from the target.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] The original reason for the use of one-pass assemblers was memory size and speed of assembly – often a second pass would require storing the symbol table in memory (to handle forward references), rewinding and rereading the program source on tape, or rereading a deck of cards or punched paper tape.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] Later computers with much larger memories (especially disc storage), had the space to perform all necessary processing without such re-reading.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] The advantage of the multi-pass assembler is that the absence of errata makes the linking process (or the program load if the assembler directly produces executable code) faster.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] See Language design below for more details.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] A program written in assembly language consists of a series of mnemonic processor instructions and meta-statements (known variously as declarative operations, directives, pseudo-instructions, pseudo-operations and pseudo-ops), comments and data.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] Assembly language instructions usually consist of an opcode mnemonic followed by an operand, which might be a list of data, arguments or parameters.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] Some instructions may be "implied", which means the data upon which the instruction operates is implicitly defined by the instruction itself—such an instruction does not take an operand.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] The resulting statement is translated by an assembler into machine language instructions that can be loaded into memory and executed.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] For example, the instruction below tells an x86/IA-32 processor to move an immediate 8-bit value into a register.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] The binary code for this instruction is 10110 followed by a 3-bit identifier for which register to use.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] The identifier for the *AL* register is 000, so the following machine code loads the *AL* register with the data 01100001.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] This binary computer code can be made more human-readable by expressing it in hexadecimal as follows.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] Here, `B0` means "Move a copy of the following value into *AL*", and `61` is a hexadecimal representation of the value 01100001, which is 97 in decimal.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] Assembly language for the 8086 family provides the mnemonic MOV (an abbreviation of *move*) for instructions such as this, so the machine code above can be written as follows in assembly language, complete with an explanatory comment if required, after the semicolon.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] This is much easier to read and to remember.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] Other assemblers may use separate opcode mnemonics such as L for "move memory to register", ST for "move register to memory", LR for "move register to register", MVI for "move immediate operand to memory", etc.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] If the same mnemonic is used for different instructions, that means that the mnemonic corresponds to several different binary instruction codes, excluding data (e.g. the `61h` in this example), depending on the operands that follow the mnemonic.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] For example, for the x86/IA-32 CPUs, the Intel assembly language syntax `MOV AL, AH` represents an instruction that moves the contents of register *AH* into register *AL*.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] The first byte, 88h, identifies a move between a byte-sized register and either another register or memory, and the second byte, E0h, is encoded (with three bit-fields) to specify that both operands are registers, the source is *AH*, and the destination is *AL*.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] In a case like this where the same mnemonic can represent more than one binary instruction, the assembler determines which instruction to generate by examining the operands.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] In the first example, the operand `61h` is a valid hexadecimal numeric constant and is not a valid register name, so only the `B0` instruction can be applicable.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] In the second example, the operand `AH` is a valid register name and not a valid numeric constant (hexadecimal, decimal, octal, or binary), so only the `88` instruction can be applicable.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] Assembly languages are always designed so that this sort of lack of ambiguity is universally enforced by their syntax.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] For example, in the Intel x86 assembly language, a hexadecimal constant must start with a numeral digit, so that the hexadecimal number 'A' (equal to decimal ten) would be written as `0Ah` or `0AH`, not `AH`, specifically so that it cannot appear to be the name of register *AH*.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] Returning to the original example, while the x86 opcode 10110000 (`B0`) copies an 8-bit value into the *AL* register, 10110001 (`B1`) moves it into *CL* and 10110010 (`B2`) does so into *DL*.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] Assembly language examples for these follow.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] The syntax of MOV can also be more complex as the following examples show.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] In each case, the MOV mnemonic is translated directly into one of the opcodes 88-8C, 8E, A0-A3, B0-BF, C6 or C7 by an assembler, and the programmer normally does not have to know or remember which.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] An assembler transforms assembly language into machine code, and the reverse can at least partially be achieved by a disassembler.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] Unlike high-level languages, there is a one-to-one correspondence between many simple assembly statements and machine language instructions.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] However, in some cases, an assembler may provide *pseudoinstructions* (essentially macros) which expand into several machine language instructions to provide commonly needed functionality.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] For example, for a machine that lacks a "branch if greater or equal" instruction, an assembler may provide a pseudoinstruction that expands to the machine's "set if less than" and "branch if zero (on the result of the set instruction)".
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] Most full-featured assemblers also provide a rich macro language (discussed below) which is used by vendors and programmers to generate more complex code and data sequences.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] Likewise, since comments in the assembly language source file are ignored by the assembler and have no effect on the object code it generates, a disassembler is always completely unable to recover source comments.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] Each computer architecture has its own machine language.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] Computers differ in the number and type of operations they support, in the different sizes and numbers of registers, and in the representations of data in storage.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] While most general-purpose computers are able to carry out essentially the same functionality, the ways they do so differ; the corresponding assembly languages reflect these differences.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] Multiple sets of mnemonics or assembly-language syntax may exist for a single instruction set, typically instantiated in different assembler programs.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] In these cases, the most popular one is usually that supplied by the CPU manufacturer and used in its documentation.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] Two examples of CPUs that have two different sets of mnemonics are the Intel 8080 family and the Intel 8086/8088.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] Because Intel claimed copyright on its assembly language mnemonics (on each page of their documentation published in the 1970s and early 1980s, at least), some companies that independently produced CPUs compatible with Intel instruction sets invented their own mnemonics.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] The Zilog Z80 CPU, an enhancement of the Intel 8080A, supports all the 8080A instructions plus many more; Zilog invented an entirely new assembly language, not only for the new instructions but also for all of the 8080A instructions.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] For example, where Intel uses the mnemonics *MOV*, *MVI*, *LDA*, *STA*, *LXI*, *LDAX*, *STAX*, *LHLD*, and *SHLD* for various data transfer instructions, the Z80 assembly language uses the mnemonic *LD* for all of them.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] A similar case is the NEC V20 and V30 CPUs, enhanced copies of the Intel 8086 and 8088, respectively.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] Like Zilog with the Z80, NEC invented new mnemonics for all of the 8086 and 8088 instructions, to avoid accusations of infringement of Intel's copyright.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] "Hello, world!" can be printed using 32-bit assembly language for an x86 processor with little help from an operating system.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] "Call outchr" calls some mechanism that prints a character in AL to the console.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] A non zero-length string must be terminated with a byte of zero.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] There is a large degree of diversity in the way the authors of assemblers categorize statements and in the nomenclature that they use.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] In particular, some describe anything other than a machine mnemonic or extended mnemonic as a pseudo-operation (pseudo-op).
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] Instructions (statements) in assembly language are generally very simple, unlike those in high-level languages.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] Generally, a mnemonic is a symbolic name for a single executable machine language instruction (an opcode), and there is at least one opcode mnemonic defined for each machine language instruction.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] Each instruction typically consists of an *operation* or *opcode* plus zero or more *operands*.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] Most instructions refer to a single value or a pair of values.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] Operands can be immediate (value coded in the instruction itself), registers specified in the instruction or implied, or the addresses of data located elsewhere in storage.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] This is determined by the underlying processor architecture: the assembler merely reflects how this architecture works.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] *Extended mnemonics* are often used to specify a combination of an opcode with a specific operand, e.g., the System/360 assemblers use `B` as an extended mnemonic for `BC` with a mask of 15 and `NOP` ("NO OPeration" – do nothing for one step) for `BC` with a mask of 0.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] Some assemblers also support simple built-in macro-instructions that generate two or more machine instructions.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] For instance, with some Z80 assemblers the instruction `ld hl,bc` is recognized to generate `ld l,c` followed by `ld h,b`.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] These are sometimes known as *pseudo-opcodes*.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] Mnemonics are arbitrary symbols; in 1985 the IEEE published Standard 694 for a uniform set of mnemonics to be used by all assemblers.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] There are instructions used to define data elements to hold data and variables.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] They define the type of data, the length and the alignment of data.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] These instructions can also define whether the data is available to outside programs (programs assembled separately) or only to the program in which the data section is defined.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] Some assemblers classify these as pseudo-ops.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] Assembly directives, also called pseudo-opcodes, pseudo-operations or pseudo-ops, are commands given to an assembler "directing it to perform operations other than assembling instructions".
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] Directives affect how the assembler operates and "may affect the object code, the symbol table, the listing file, and the values of internal assembler parameters".
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] Sometimes the term *pseudo-opcode* is reserved for directives that generate object code, such as those that generate data.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] The names of pseudo-ops often start with a dot to distinguish them from machine instructions.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] Pseudo-ops can make the assembly of the program dependent on parameters input by a programmer, so that one program can be assembled in different ways, perhaps for different applications.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] Or, a pseudo-op can be used to manipulate presentation of a program to make it easier to read and maintain.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] Another common use of pseudo-ops is to reserve storage areas for run-time data and optionally initialize their contents to known values.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] Symbolic assemblers let programmers associate arbitrary names (*labels* or *symbols*) with memory locations and various constants.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] Usually, every constant and variable is given a name so instructions can reference those locations by name, thus promoting self-documenting code.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] In executable code, the name of each subroutine is associated with its entry point, so any calls to a subroutine can use its name.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] Inside subroutines, GOTO destinations are given labels.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] Some assemblers support *local symbols* which are often lexically distinct from normal symbols (e.g., the use of "10$" as a GOTO destination).
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] Some assemblers, such as NASM, provide flexible symbol management, letting programmers manage different namespaces, automatically calculate offsets within data structures, and assign labels that refer to literal values or the result of simple computations performed by the assembler.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] Labels can also be used to initialize constants and variables with relocatable addresses.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] Assembly languages, like most other computer languages, allow comments to be added to program source code that will be ignored during assembly.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] Judicious commenting is essential in assembly language programs, as the meaning and purpose of a sequence of binary machine instructions can be difficult to determine.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] The "raw" (uncommented) assembly language generated by compilers or disassemblers is quite difficult to read when changes must be made.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] Many assemblers support *predefined macros*, and others support *programmer-defined* (and repeatedly re-definable) macros involving sequences of text lines in which variables and constants are embedded.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] The macro definition is most commonly a mixture of assembler statements, e.g., directives, symbolic machine instructions, and templates for assembler statements.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] This sequence of text lines may include opcodes or directives.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] Once a macro has been defined its name may be used in place of a mnemonic.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] When the assembler processes such a statement, it replaces the statement with the text lines associated with that macro, then processes them as if they existed in the source code file (including, in some assemblers, expansion of any macros existing in the replacement text).
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] Macros in this sense date to IBM autocoders of the 1950s.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] In assembly language, the term "macro" represents a more comprehensive concept than it does in some other contexts, such as the pre-processor in the C programming language, where its #define directive typically is used to create short single line macros.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] Assembler macro instructions, like macros in PL/I and some other languages, can be lengthy "programs" by themselves, executed by interpretation by the assembler during assembly.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] Since macros can have 'short' names but expand to several or indeed many lines of code, they can be used to make assembly language programs appear to be far shorter, requiring fewer lines of source code, as with higher level languages.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] They can also be used to add higher levels of structure to assembly programs, optionally introduce embedded debugging code via parameters and other similar features.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] Macro assemblers often allow macros to take parameters.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] Thus a macro might generate numerous assembly language instructions or data definitions, based on the macro arguments.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] This could be used to generate record-style data structures or "unrolled" loops, for example, or could generate entire algorithms based on complex parameters.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] For instance, a "sort" macro could accept the specification of a complex sort key and generate code crafted for that specific key, not needing the run-time tests that would be required for a general procedure interpreting the specification.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] An organization using assembly language that has been heavily extended using such a macro suite can be considered to be working in a higher-level language since such programmers are not working with a computer's lowest-level conceptual elements.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] Underlining this point, macros were used to implement an early virtual machine in SNOBOL4 (1967), which was written in the SNOBOL Implementation Language (SIL), an assembly language for a virtual machine.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] The target machine would translate this to its native code using a macro assembler.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] This allowed a high degree of portability for the time.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] Macros were used to customize large scale software systems for specific customers in the mainframe era and were also used by customer personnel to satisfy their employers' needs by making specific versions of manufacturer operating systems.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] IBM OS/360 uses macros to perform system generation.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] The user specifies options by coding a series of assembler macros.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] Assembling these macros generates a job stream to build the system, including job control language and utility control statements.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] This is because, as was realized in the 1960s, the concept of "macro processing" is independent of the concept of "assembly", the former being in modern terms more word processing, text processing, than generating object code.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] The concept of macro processing appeared, and appears, in the C programming language, which supports "preprocessor instructions" to set variables, and make conditional tests on their values.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] Unlike certain previous macro processors inside assemblers, the C preprocessor is not Turing-complete because it lacks the ability to either loop or "go to", the latter allowing programs to loop.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] Despite the power of macro processing, it fell into disuse in many high level languages (major exceptions being C, C++ and PL/I) while remaining a perennial for assemblers.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] Macro parameter substitution is strictly by name: at macro processing time, the value of a parameter is textually substituted for its name.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] The most famous class of bugs resulting was the use of a parameter that itself was an expression and not a simple name when the macro writer expected a name.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] the intention was that the caller would provide the name of a variable, and the "global" variable or constant b would be used to multiply "a".
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] If foo is called with the parameter `a-c`, the macro expansion of `load a-c*b` occurs.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] To avoid any possible ambiguity, users of macro processors can parenthesize formal parameters inside macro definitions, or callers can parenthesize the input parameters.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] Packages of macros have been written providing structured programming elements to encode execution flow.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] The earliest example of this approach was in the Concept-14 macro set, originally proposed by Harlan Mills (March 1970), and implemented by Marvin Kessler at IBM's Federal Systems Division, which provided IF/ELSE/ENDIF and similar control flow blocks for OS/360 assembler programs.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] This was a way to reduce or eliminate the use of GOTO operations in assembly code, one of the main factors causing spaghetti code in assembly language.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] This approach was widely accepted in the early 1980s (the latter days of large-scale assembly language use).
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] IBM's High Level Assembler Toolkit includes such a macro package.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] Another design was A-Natural, a "stream-oriented" assembler for 8080/Z80 processors from Whitesmiths Ltd.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] (developers of the Unix-like Idris operating system, and what was reported to be the first commercial C compiler).
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] The language was classified as an assembler because it worked with raw machine elements such as opcodes, registers, and memory references; but it incorporated an expression syntax to indicate execution order.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] Parentheses and other special symbols, along with block-oriented structured programming constructs, controlled the sequence of the generated instructions.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] A-natural was built as the object language of a C compiler, rather than for hand-coding, but its logical syntax won some fans.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] There has been little apparent demand for more sophisticated assemblers since the decline of large-scale assembly language development.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p01] In spite of that, they are still being developed and applied in cases where resource constraints or peculiarities in the target system's architecture prevent the effective use of higher-level languages.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p02] When the stored-program computer was introduced, programs were written in machine code, and loaded into the computer from punched paper tape or toggled directly into memory from console switches.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p02] In late 1948, the Electronic Delay Storage Automatic Calculator (EDSAC) had an assembler (named "initial orders") integrated into its bootstrap program.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p02] It used one-letter mnemonics developed by David Wheeler, who is credited by the IEEE Computer Society as the creator of the first "assembler".
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p02] Reports on the EDSAC introduced the term "assembly" for the process of combining fields into an instruction word.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p02] SOAP (Symbolic Optimal Assembly Program) was an assembly language for the IBM 650 computer written by Stan Poley in 1955.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p02] Assembly languages eliminated much of the error-prone, tedious, and time-consuming first-generation programming needed with the earliest computers, freeing programmers from tedium such as remembering numeric codes and calculating addresses.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p02] They were once widely used for all sorts of programming.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p02] By the late 1950s their use had largely been supplanted by higher-level languages in the search for improved programming productivity.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p02] Today, assembly language is still used for direct hardware manipulation, access to specialized processor instructions, or to address critical performance issues.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p02] Typical uses are device drivers, low-level embedded systems, and real-time systems (see § Current usage).
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p02] Numerous programs were written entirely in assembly language.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p02] The Burroughs MCP (1961) was the first computer for which an operating system was not developed entirely in assembly language; it was written in Executive Systems Problem Oriented Language (ESPOL), an Algol dialect.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p02] Many commercial applications were written in assembly language as well, including a large amount of the IBM mainframe software developed by large corporations.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p02] COBOL, FORTRAN and some PL/I eventually displaced assembly language, although a number of large organizations retained assembly-language application infrastructures well into the 1990s.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p02] Assembly language was the primary development language for 8-bit home computers such as the Apple II, Atari 8-bit computers, ZX Spectrum, and Commodore 64.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p02] Interpreted BASIC on these systems did not offer maximum execution speed and full use of facilities to take full advantage of the available hardware.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p02] Assembly language was the default choice for programming 8-bit consoles such as the Atari 2600 and Nintendo Entertainment System.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p02] Key software for IBM PC compatibles such as MS-DOS, Turbo Pascal, and the Lotus 1-2-3 spreadsheet was written in assembly language.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p02] As computer speed grew exponentially, assembly language became a tool for speeding up parts of programs, such as the rendering of *Doom*, rather than a dominant development language.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p02] In the 1990s, assembly language was used to maximise performance from systems such as the Sega Saturn, and as the primary language for arcade hardware using the TMS34010 integrated CPU/GPU such as *Mortal Kombat* and *NBA Jam*.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p02] There has been debate over the usefulness and performance of assembly language relative to high-level languages.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p02] Although assembly language has specific niche uses where it is important (see below), there are other tools for optimization.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p02] As of July 2017, the TIOBE index of programming language popularity ranks assembly language at 11, ahead of Visual Basic, for example.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p02] Assembler can be used to optimize for speed or optimize for size.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p02] In the case of speed optimization, modern optimizing compilers are claimed to render high-level languages into code that can run as fast as hand-written assembly, despite some counter-examples.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p02] The complexity of modern processors and memory sub-systems makes effective optimization increasingly difficult for compilers and assembly programmers alike.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p02] Increasing processor performance has meant that most CPUs sit idle most of the time, with delays caused by predictable bottlenecks such as cache misses, I/O operations and paging, making raw code execution speed a non-issue for many programmers.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p02] Assembly language is still taught in most computer science and electronic engineering programs.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p02] Although few programmers today regularly work with assembly language as a tool, the underlying concepts remain important.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p02] Such fundamental topics as binary arithmetic, memory allocation, stack processing, character set encoding, interrupt processing, and compiler design would be hard to study in detail without a grasp of how a computer operates at the hardware level.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p02] Since a computer's behaviour is fundamentally defined by its instruction set, the logical way to learn such concepts is to study an assembly language.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p02] Most modern computers have similar instruction sets.
[src:disassembly-analysis/assembly-language-p02] Therefore, studying a single assembly language is sufficient to learn the basic concepts, recognize situations where the use of assembly language might be appropriate, and to see how efficient executable code can be created from high-level languages.
[src:disassembly-analysis/binary-code] A **binary code** is the value of a data-encoding convention represented in a binary notation that usually is a sequence of 0s and 1s, sometimes called a *bit string*.
[src:disassembly-analysis/binary-code] For example, ASCII is an 8-bit text encoding that in addition to the human readable form (letters) can be represented as binary.
[src:disassembly-analysis/binary-code] *Binary code* can also refer to the mass noun *code* that is not human readable in nature such as machine code and bytecode.
[src:disassembly-analysis/binary-code] Even though all modern computer data is binary in nature, and therefore can be represented as binary, other numerical bases may be used.
[src:disassembly-analysis/binary-code] Power of 2 bases (including hex and octal) are sometimes considered binary code since their power-of-2 nature makes them inherently linked to binary.
[src:disassembly-analysis/binary-code] Decimal is, of course, a commonly used representation.
[src:disassembly-analysis/binary-code] For example, ASCII characters are often represented as either decimal or hex.
[src:disassembly-analysis/binary-code] Some types of data such as image data is sometimes represented as hex, but rarely as decimal.
[src:disassembly-analysis/binary-code] The modern binary number system, the basis for binary code, is an invention by Gottfried Leibniz in 1689 and appears in his article *Explication de l'Arithmétique Binaire (*English: *Explanation of the Binary Arithmetic*) which uses only the characters 1 and 0, and some remarks on its usefulness.
[src:disassembly-analysis/binary-code] Leibniz's system uses 0 and 1, like the modern binary numeral system.
[src:disassembly-analysis/binary-code] Binary numerals were central to Leibniz's intellectual and theological ideas.
[src:disassembly-analysis/binary-code] He believed that binary numbers were symbolic of the Christian idea of *creatio ex nihilo* or creation out of nothing.
[src:disassembly-analysis/binary-code] In Leibniz's view, binary numbers represented a fundamental form of creation, reflecting the simplicity and unity of the divine.
[src:disassembly-analysis/binary-code] Leibniz was also attempting to find a way to translate logical reasoning into pure mathematics.
[src:disassembly-analysis/binary-code] He viewed the binary system as a means of simplifying complex logical and mathematical processes, believing that it could be used to express all concepts of arithmetic and logic.
[src:disassembly-analysis/binary-code] Leibniz saw the hexagrams as an affirmation of the universality of his own religious belief.
[src:disassembly-analysis/binary-code] After Leibniz ideas were ignored, the book had confirmed his theory that life could be simplified or reduced down to a series of straightforward propositions.
[src:disassembly-analysis/binary-code] He created a system consisting of rows of zeros and ones.
[src:disassembly-analysis/binary-code] During this time period, Leibniz had not yet found a use for this system.
[src:disassembly-analysis/binary-code] The binary system of the *I Ching* is based on the duality of yin and yang.
[src:disassembly-analysis/binary-code] Slit drums with binary tones are used to encode messages across Africa and Asia.
[src:disassembly-analysis/binary-code] The Indian scholar Pingala (around 5th–2nd centuries BC) developed a binary system for describing prosody in his *Chandashutram*.
[src:disassembly-analysis/binary-code] Mangareva people in French Polynesia were using a hybrid binary-decimal system before 1450.
[src:disassembly-analysis/binary-code] In the 11th century, scholar and philosopher Shao Yong developed a method for arranging the hexagrams which corresponds, albeit unintentionally, to the sequence 0 to 63, as represented in binary, with yin as 0, yang as 1 and the least significant bit on top.
[src:disassembly-analysis/binary-code] The ordering is also the lexicographical order on sextuples of elements chosen from a two-element set.
[src:disassembly-analysis/binary-code] In 1605 Francis Bacon discussed a system whereby letters of the alphabet could be reduced to sequences of binary digits, which could then be encoded as scarcely visible variations in the font in any random text.
[src:disassembly-analysis/binary-code] Importantly for the general theory of binary encoding, he added that this method could be used with any objects at all: "provided those objects be capable of a twofold difference only; as by Bells, by Trumpets, by Lights and Torches, by the report of Muskets, and any instruments of like nature".
[src:disassembly-analysis/binary-code] George Boole published a paper in 1847 called 'The Mathematical Analysis of Logic' that describes an algebraic system of logic, now known as Boolean algebra.
[src:disassembly-analysis/binary-code] Boole's system was based on binary, a yes-no, on-off approach that consisted of the three most basic operations: AND, OR, and NOT.
[src:disassembly-analysis/binary-code] This system was not put into use until a graduate student from Massachusetts Institute of Technology, Claude Shannon, noticed that the Boolean algebra he learned was similar to an electric circuit.
[src:disassembly-analysis/binary-code] In 1937, Shannon wrote his master's thesis, *A Symbolic Analysis of Relay and Switching Circuits*, which implemented his findings.
[src:disassembly-analysis/binary-code] Shannon's thesis became a starting point for the use of the binary code in practical applications such as computers, electric circuits, and more.
[src:disassembly-analysis/binary-code] A binary code can be rendered using any two distinguishable indications.
[src:disassembly-analysis/binary-code] In addition to the bit string, other notable ways to render a binary code are described below.
[src:disassembly-analysis/binary-code] is a binary code that is widely used to enable the blind to read and write by touch.
[src:disassembly-analysis/binary-code] The system consists of grids of six dots each, three per column, in which each dot is either raised or flat (not raised).
[src:disassembly-analysis/binary-code] The different combinations of raised and flat dots encode information such as letters, numbers, and punctuation.
[src:disassembly-analysis/binary-code] , consists of an elaborate traditional ceremony producing 256 oracles made up by 16 symbols with 256 = 16 x 16.
[src:disassembly-analysis/binary-code] , requests sacrifice from consulting clients and makes prayers.
[src:disassembly-analysis/binary-code] which are drawn with sandy material on an "Opun" figured wooden tray representing the totality of fate.
[src:disassembly-analysis/binary-code] Some notable examples are described here.
[src:disassembly-analysis/binary-code] Each printing and control character is assigned a number from 0 to 127.
[src:disassembly-analysis/binary-code] As a decimal digit is only 1 of 10 values (0 to 9) but 4 bits can encode up to 16 values, and BCD element is invalid for a value greater than 9.
[src:disassembly-analysis/binary-ninja] Binary Ninja supports various CPU architectures and binary executable formats, and runs on Windows, macOS, and Linux.
[src:disassembly-analysis/binary-ninja] It also offers a free-to-use cloud version and a native commercial version.
[src:disassembly-analysis/binary-ninja] Originally developed as an internal tool for a CTF team, the developers later formed Vector 35 Inc. to turn Binary Ninja into a commercial product.
[src:disassembly-analysis/binary-ninja] Development began in 2015, and the first public version was released in July 2016.
[src:disassembly-analysis/binary-ninja] The commercial version was developed from scratch and does not share code with the original internal tool.
[src:disassembly-analysis/binary-ninja] The latter one is now open-sourced under the GPLv2 license.
[src:disassembly-analysis/binary-ninja] Binary Ninja's user interface is built using Qt and comprises several components such as a symbol list, a cross-reference window, and disassembly views (both linear and graph-based), a mini-graph, and a feature map.
[src:disassembly-analysis/binary-ninja] It also includes tools like a hex editor, strings listing, and a triage view.
[src:disassembly-analysis/binary-ninja] Binary Ninja generates extensive annotations in the UI to assist binary analysis and also supports user-defined themes for customization.
[src:disassembly-analysis/binary-ninja] Binary Ninja offers an API that can be accessed via Python, C++, or Rust.
[src:disassembly-analysis/binary-ninja] The API is open-sourced under the MIT License.
[src:disassembly-analysis/binary-ninja] It can interact with most of Binary Ninja's functionality, including the user interface, analysis tools, and intermediate languages (see below).
[src:disassembly-analysis/binary-ninja] Plugins can be developed using the API to enhance Binary Ninja.
[src:disassembly-analysis/binary-ninja] Vector35 maintains a collection of official plugins, while the community has created numerous additional plugins.
[src:disassembly-analysis/binary-ninja] Some notable plugins include the debugger, and the signature kit.
[src:disassembly-analysis/binary-ninja] Binary Ninja offers three intermediate languages (ILs).
[src:disassembly-analysis/binary-ninja] Binary Ninja automatically performs various analyses on the binary.
[src:disassembly-analysis/binary-ninja] Binary Ninja offers binary patching and editing features.
[src:disassembly-analysis/binary-ninja] It can assemble an instruction at the current line, flip a conditional jump, etc.
[src:disassembly-analysis/binary-ninja] Edits and updated analysis are immediately reflected in the UI.
[src:disassembly-analysis/binary-ninja] Binary Ninja can be used as a general binary editor.
[src:disassembly-analysis/binary-ninja] It supports several commonly used transformations and encryption algorithms.
[src:disassembly-analysis/binary-ninja] The shellcode compiler allows the user to compile and insert code via C syntax.
[src:disassembly-analysis/binary-ninja] The support for these architectures vary and details can be found in the official FAQ.
[src:disassembly-analysis/binary-ninja] Community-authored plugins add support for various other architectures.
[src:disassembly-analysis/instruction-set-architecture] An **instruction set architecture** (**ISA**) is an abstract model that defines the programmable interface of the CPU of a computer, defining how software interacts with hardware.
[src:disassembly-analysis/instruction-set-architecture] CPU) that interprets instructions described by an ISA is an implementation of that ISA.
[src:disassembly-analysis/instruction-set-architecture] Generally, the same ISA is used for a family of related CPU devices.
[src:disassembly-analysis/instruction-set-architecture] In general, an ISA defines the instructions, data types, registers, and the programming interface for managing main memory such as addressing modes, virtual memory, and memory consistency mechanisms.
[src:disassembly-analysis/instruction-set-architecture] The ISA also includes the input/output model of the programmable interface.
[src:disassembly-analysis/instruction-set-architecture] An ISA specifies the behavior implied by machine code running on an implementation of that ISA in a fashion that does not depend on the characteristics of that implementation, providing binary compatibility between implementations.
[src:disassembly-analysis/instruction-set-architecture] It also enables the evolution of the microarchitectures of the implementations of that ISA, so that a newer, higher-performance implementation of an ISA can run software that runs on previous generations of implementations.
[src:disassembly-analysis/instruction-set-architecture] If an operating system maintains a standard and compatible application binary interface (ABI) for a particular ISA, machine code will run on future implementations of that ISA and operating system.
[src:disassembly-analysis/instruction-set-architecture] However, if an ISA supports running multiple operating systems, it does not guarantee that machine code for one operating system will run on another operating system, unless the first operating system supports running machine code built for the other operating system.
[src:disassembly-analysis/instruction-set-architecture] An ISA can be extended by adding instructions or other capabilities, or adding support for larger addresses and data values; an implementation of the extended ISA will still be able to execute machine code for versions of the ISA without those extensions.
[src:disassembly-analysis/instruction-set-architecture] Machine code using those extensions will only run on implementations that support those extensions.
[src:disassembly-analysis/instruction-set-architecture] The binary compatibility that they provide makes ISAs one of the most fundamental abstractions in computing.
[src:disassembly-analysis/instruction-set-architecture] An instruction set architecture is distinguished from a microarchitecture, which is the set of processor design techniques used, in a particular processor, to implement the instruction set.
[src:disassembly-analysis/instruction-set-architecture] Processors with different microarchitectures can share a common instruction set.
[src:disassembly-analysis/instruction-set-architecture] For example, the Intel Pentium and the AMD Athlon implement nearly identical versions of the x86 instruction set, but they have radically different internal designs.
[src:disassembly-analysis/instruction-set-architecture] The concept of an *architecture*, distinct from the design of a specific machine, was developed by Fred Brooks at IBM during the design phase of System/360.
[src:disassembly-analysis/instruction-set-architecture] Some virtual machines that support bytecode as their ISA such as Smalltalk, the Java virtual machine, and Microsoft's Common Language Runtime, implement this by translating the bytecode for commonly used code paths into native machine code.
[src:disassembly-analysis/instruction-set-architecture] In addition, these virtual machines execute less frequently used code paths by interpretation (see: Just-in-time compilation).
[src:disassembly-analysis/instruction-set-architecture] Transmeta implemented the x86 instruction set atop very long instruction word (VLIW) processors in this fashion.
[src:disassembly-analysis/instruction-set-architecture] An ISA may be classified in a number of different ways.
[src:disassembly-analysis/instruction-set-architecture] A common classification is by architectural *complexity*.
[src:disassembly-analysis/instruction-set-architecture] A complex instruction set computer (CISC) has many specialized instructions, some of which may only be rarely used in practical programs.
[src:disassembly-analysis/instruction-set-architecture] Other types include VLIW architectures, and the closely related *long instruction word* (LIW) and *explicitly parallel instruction computing* (EPIC) architectures.
[src:disassembly-analysis/instruction-set-architecture] These architectures seek to exploit instruction-level parallelism with less hardware than RISC and CISC by making the compiler responsible for instruction issue and scheduling.
[src:disassembly-analysis/instruction-set-architecture] Architectures with even less complexity have been studied, such as the minimal instruction set computer (MISC) and one-instruction set computer (OISC).
[src:disassembly-analysis/instruction-set-architecture] These are theoretically important types, but have not been commercialized.
[src:disassembly-analysis/instruction-set-architecture] Machine language is built up from discrete *statements* or *instructions*.
[src:disassembly-analysis/instruction-set-architecture] More complex operations are built up by combining these simple instructions, which are executed sequentially, or as otherwise directed by control flow instructions.
[src:disassembly-analysis/instruction-set-architecture] Processors may include elaborate instructions in their instruction set.
[src:disassembly-analysis/instruction-set-architecture] A single elaborate instruction does something that may require many instructions or a subroutine on other computers.
[src:disassembly-analysis/instruction-set-architecture] Such instructions are typified by instructions that take multiple steps, control multiple functional units, or otherwise appear on a larger scale than the bulk of simple instructions implemented by the given processor.
[src:disassembly-analysis/instruction-set-architecture] Elaborate instructions are more common in CISC instruction sets than in RISC instruction sets, but RISC instruction sets may include them as well.
[src:disassembly-analysis/instruction-set-architecture] RISC instruction sets generally do not include ALU operations with memory operands, or instructions to move large blocks of memory, but most RISC instruction sets include SIMD or vector instructions that perform the same arithmetic operation on multiple pieces of data at the same time.
[src:disassembly-analysis/instruction-set-architecture] SIMD instructions have the ability of manipulating large vectors and matrices in minimal time.
[src:disassembly-analysis/instruction-set-architecture] SIMD instructions allow easy parallelization of algorithms commonly involved in sound, image, and video processing.
[src:disassembly-analysis/instruction-set-architecture] Various SIMD implementations have been brought to market under trade names such as MMX, 3DNow!, and AltiVec.
[src:disassembly-analysis/instruction-set-architecture] On traditional architectures, an instruction includes an opcode that specifies the operation to perform, such as *add contents of memory to register*—and zero or more operand specifiers, which may specify registers, memory locations, or literal data.
[src:disassembly-analysis/instruction-set-architecture] The operand specifiers may have addressing modes determining their meaning or may be in fixed fields.
[src:disassembly-analysis/instruction-set-architecture] In very long instruction word (VLIW) architectures, which include many microcode architectures, multiple simultaneous opcodes and operands are specified in a single instruction.
[src:disassembly-analysis/instruction-set-architecture] Some exotic instruction sets do not have an opcode field, such as transport triggered architectures (TTA), only operand(s).
[src:disassembly-analysis/instruction-set-architecture] Most stack machines have "0-operand" instruction sets in which arithmetic and logical operations lack any operand specifier fields; only instructions that push operands onto the evaluation stack or that pop operands from the stack into variables have operand specifiers.
[src:disassembly-analysis/instruction-set-architecture] The instruction set carries out most ALU actions with postfix (reverse Polish notation) operations that work only on the expression stack, not on data registers or arbitrary main memory cells.
[src:disassembly-analysis/instruction-set-architecture] This can be very convenient for compiling high-level languages, because most arithmetic expressions can be easily translated into postfix notation.
[src:disassembly-analysis/instruction-set-architecture] Conditional instructions often have a predicate field—a few bits that encode the specific condition to cause an operation to be performed rather than not performed.
[src:disassembly-analysis/instruction-set-architecture] For example, a conditional branch instruction will transfer control if the condition is true, so that execution proceeds to a different part of the program, and not transfer control if the condition is false, so that execution continues sequentially.
[src:disassembly-analysis/instruction-set-architecture] Some instruction sets also have conditional moves, so that the move will be executed, and the data stored in the target location, if the condition is true, and not executed, and the target location not modified, if the condition is false.
[src:disassembly-analysis/instruction-set-architecture] Similarly, IBM z/Architecture has a conditional store instruction.
[src:disassembly-analysis/instruction-set-architecture] A few instruction sets include a predicate field in every instruction.
[src:disassembly-analysis/instruction-set-architecture] Having predicates on instructions is called predication, and can *include* conditional-branches, such as `bf` on the SuperH.
[src:disassembly-analysis/instruction-set-architecture] Many architectures have conditional branch instructions designed for controlling loops.
[src:disassembly-analysis/instruction-set-architecture] Typically, they update and test a register.
[src:disassembly-analysis/instruction-set-architecture] Instruction sets may be categorized by the maximum number of operands *explicitly* specified in instructions.
[src:disassembly-analysis/instruction-set-architecture] Due to the large number of bits needed to encode the three registers of a 3-operand instruction, RISC architectures that have 16-bit instructions are invariably 2-operand designs, such as the Atmel AVR, TI MSP430, and some versions of ARM Thumb.
[src:disassembly-analysis/instruction-set-architecture] RISC architectures that have 32-bit instructions are usually 3-operand designs, such as the ARM, AVR32, MIPS, Power ISA, and SPARC architectures.
[src:disassembly-analysis/instruction-set-architecture] However even 3-operand RISC architectures will, at considerable cost, have Fused multiply-and-add 4-operand instructions out of necessity, due to the increased accuracy provided.
[src:disassembly-analysis/instruction-set-architecture] Modern examples include Power ISA and RISC-V.
[src:disassembly-analysis/instruction-set-architecture] Each instruction specifies some number of operands (registers, memory locations, or immediate values) *explicitly*.
[src:disassembly-analysis/instruction-set-architecture] Some instructions give one or both operands implicitly, such as by being stored on top of the stack or in an implicit register.
[src:disassembly-analysis/instruction-set-architecture] If some of the operands are given implicitly, fewer operands need be specified in the instruction.
[src:disassembly-analysis/instruction-set-architecture] When a "destination operand" explicitly specifies the destination, an additional operand must be supplied.
[src:disassembly-analysis/instruction-set-architecture] Consequently, the number of operands encoded in an instruction may differ from the mathematically necessary number of arguments for a logical or arithmetic operation (the arity).
[src:disassembly-analysis/instruction-set-architecture] Operands are either encoded in the "opcode" representation of the instruction, or else are given as values or addresses following the opcode.
[src:disassembly-analysis/instruction-set-architecture] While embedded instruction sets such as Thumb suffer from extremely high register pressure because they have small register sets, general-purpose RISC ISAs like MIPS and Alpha enjoy low register pressure.
[src:disassembly-analysis/instruction-set-architecture] CISC ISAs like x86-64 offer low register pressure despite having smaller register sets.
[src:disassembly-analysis/instruction-set-architecture] This is due to the many addressing modes and optimizations (such as sub-register addressing, memory operands in ALU instructions, absolute addressing, PC-relative addressing, and register-to-register spills) that CISC ISAs offer.
[src:disassembly-analysis/instruction-set-architecture] The size or length of an instruction varies widely, from as little as four bits in some microcontrollers to many hundreds of bits in some VLIW systems.
[src:disassembly-analysis/instruction-set-architecture] Processors used in personal computers, mainframes, and supercomputers have minimum instruction sizes between 8 and 64 bits.
[src:disassembly-analysis/instruction-set-architecture] The longest possible instruction on x86 is 15 bytes (120 bits).
[src:disassembly-analysis/instruction-set-architecture] Within an instruction set, different instructions may have different lengths.
[src:disassembly-analysis/instruction-set-architecture] In some architectures, notably most reduced instruction set computers (RISC), instructions are a fixed length, typically corresponding with that architecture's word size.
[src:disassembly-analysis/instruction-set-architecture] In other architectures, instructions have variable length, typically integral multiples of a byte or a halfword.
[src:disassembly-analysis/instruction-set-architecture] Some, such as the ARM with *Thumb-extension* have *mixed* variable encoding, that is two fixed, usually 32-bit and 16-bit encodings, where instructions cannot be mixed freely but must be switched between on a branch (or exception boundary in ARMv8).
[src:disassembly-analysis/instruction-set-architecture] Fixed-length instructions are less complicated to handle than variable-length instructions for several reasons (not having to check whether an instruction straddles a cache line or virtual memory page boundary, for instance), and are therefore somewhat easier to optimize for speed.
[src:disassembly-analysis/instruction-set-architecture] In early 1960s computers, main memory was expensive and very limited, even on mainframes.
[src:disassembly-analysis/instruction-set-architecture] Minimizing the size of a program to make sure it would fit in the limited memory was often central.
[src:disassembly-analysis/instruction-set-architecture] Thus the size of the instructions needed to perform a particular task, the *code density*, was an important characteristic of any instruction set.
[src:disassembly-analysis/instruction-set-architecture] It remained important on the initially-tiny memories of minicomputers and then microprocessors.
[src:disassembly-analysis/instruction-set-architecture] Density remains important today, for smartphone applications, applications downloaded into browsers over slow Internet connections, and in ROMs for embedded applications.
[src:disassembly-analysis/instruction-set-architecture] A more general advantage of increased density is improved effectiveness of caches and instruction prefetch.
[src:disassembly-analysis/instruction-set-architecture] Computers with high code density often have complex instructions for procedure entry, parameterized returns, loops, etc.
[src:disassembly-analysis/instruction-set-architecture] (therefore retroactively named *Complex Instruction Set Computers*, CISC).
[src:disassembly-analysis/instruction-set-architecture] However, more typical, or frequent, "CISC" instructions merely combine a basic ALU operation, such as "add", with the access of one or more operands in memory (using addressing modes such as direct, indirect, indexed, etc.).
[src:disassembly-analysis/instruction-set-architecture] Certain architectures may allow two or three operands (including the result) directly in memory or may be able to perform functions such as automatic pointer increment, etc.
[src:disassembly-analysis/instruction-set-architecture] Software-implemented instruction sets may have even more complex and powerful instructions.
[src:disassembly-analysis/instruction-set-architecture] Certain embedded RISC ISAs like Thumb and AVR32 typically exhibit very high density owing to a technique called code compression.
[src:disassembly-analysis/instruction-set-architecture] This technique packs two 16-bit instructions into one 32-bit word, which is then unpacked at the decode stage and executed as two instructions.
[src:disassembly-analysis/instruction-set-architecture] Minimal instruction set computers (MISC) are commonly a form of stack machine, where there are few separate instructions (8–32), so that multiple instructions can be fit into a single machine word.
[src:disassembly-analysis/instruction-set-architecture] These types of cores often take little silicon to implement, so they can be easily realized in an FPGA (field-programmable gate array) or in a multi-core form.
[src:disassembly-analysis/instruction-set-architecture] The code density of MISC is similar to the code density of RISC; the increased instruction density is offset by requiring more of the primitive instructions to do a task.
[src:disassembly-analysis/instruction-set-architecture] There has been research into executable compression as a mechanism for improving code density.
[src:disassembly-analysis/instruction-set-architecture] The mathematics of Kolmogorov complexity describes the challenges and limits of this.
[src:disassembly-analysis/instruction-set-architecture] In practice, code density is also dependent on the compiler.
[src:disassembly-analysis/instruction-set-architecture] Most optimizing compilers have options that control whether to optimize code generation for execution speed or for code density.
[src:disassembly-analysis/instruction-set-architecture] For instance GCC has the option `-Os` to optimize for small machine code size, and `-O3` to optimize for execution speed at the cost of larger machine code.
[src:disassembly-analysis/instruction-set-architecture] The instructions constituting a program are rarely specified using their internal, numeric form (machine code); they may be specified by programmers using an assembly language or, more commonly, may be generated from high-level programming languages by compilers.
[src:disassembly-analysis/instruction-set-architecture] The design of instruction sets is a complex issue.
[src:disassembly-analysis/instruction-set-architecture] There were two stages in history for the microprocessor.
[src:disassembly-analysis/instruction-set-architecture] The first was the CISC (complex instruction set computer), which had many different instructions.
[src:disassembly-analysis/instruction-set-architecture] In the 1970s, however, places like IBM did research and found that many instructions in the set could be eliminated.
[src:disassembly-analysis/instruction-set-architecture] The result was the RISC (reduced instruction set computer), an architecture that uses a smaller set of instructions.
[src:disassembly-analysis/instruction-set-architecture] A simpler instruction set may offer the potential for higher speeds, reduced processor size, and reduced power consumption.
[src:disassembly-analysis/instruction-set-architecture] However, a more complex set may optimize common operations, improve memory and cache efficiency, or simplify programming.
[src:disassembly-analysis/instruction-set-architecture] Some instruction set designers reserve one or more opcodes for some kind of system call or software interrupt.
[src:disassembly-analysis/instruction-set-architecture] For example, MOS Technology 6502 uses 00H, Zilog Z80 uses the eight codes C7,CF,D7,DF,E7,EF,F7,FFH while Motorola 68000 use codes in the range 4E40H-4E4FH.
[src:disassembly-analysis/instruction-set-architecture] Fast virtual machines are much easier to implement if an instruction set meets the Popek and Goldberg virtualization requirements.
[src:disassembly-analysis/instruction-set-architecture] The NOP slide used in immunity-aware programming is much easier to implement if the "unprogrammed" state of the memory is interpreted as a NOP.
[src:disassembly-analysis/instruction-set-architecture] On systems with multiple processors, non-blocking synchronization algorithms are much easier to implement if the instruction set includes support for something such as "fetch-and-add", "load-link/store-conditional" (LL/SC), or "atomic compare-and-swap".
[src:disassembly-analysis/instruction-set-architecture] A given instruction set can be implemented in a variety of ways.
[src:disassembly-analysis/instruction-set-architecture] All ways of implementing a particular instruction set provide the same programming model, and all implementations of that instruction set are able to run the same executables.
[src:disassembly-analysis/instruction-set-architecture] The various ways of implementing an instruction set give different tradeoffs between cost, performance, power consumption, size, etc.
[src:disassembly-analysis/instruction-set-architecture] When designing the microarchitecture of a processor, engineers use blocks of "hard-wired" electronic circuitry (often designed separately) such as adders, multiplexers, counters, registers, ALUs, etc.
[src:disassembly-analysis/instruction-set-architecture] Some kind of register transfer language is then often used to describe the decoding and sequencing of each instruction of an ISA using this physical microarchitecture.
[src:disassembly-analysis/instruction-set-architecture] Other designs employ microcode routines or tables (or both) to do this, using ROMs or writable RAMs (writable control store), PLAs, or both.
[src:disassembly-analysis/instruction-set-architecture] Some microcoded CPU designs with a writable control store use it to allow the instruction set to be changed (for example, the Rekursiv processor and the Imsys Cjip).
[src:disassembly-analysis/instruction-set-architecture] CPUs designed for reconfigurable computing may use field-programmable gate arrays (FPGAs).
[src:disassembly-analysis/instruction-set-architecture] An ISA can also be emulated in software by an interpreter.
[src:disassembly-analysis/instruction-set-architecture] Naturally, due to the interpretation overhead, this is slower than directly running programs on the emulated hardware, unless the hardware running the emulator is an order of magnitude faster.
[src:disassembly-analysis/instruction-set-architecture] Today, it is common practice for vendors of new ISAs or microarchitectures to make software emulators available to software developers before the hardware implementation is ready.
[src:disassembly-analysis/instruction-set-architecture] Often the details of the implementation have a strong influence on the particular instructions selected for the instruction set.
[src:disassembly-analysis/instruction-set-architecture] For example, many implementations of the instruction pipeline only allow a single memory load or memory store per instruction, leading to a load–store architecture (RISC).
[src:disassembly-analysis/instruction-set-architecture] For another example, some early ways of implementing the instruction pipeline led to a delay slot.
[src:disassembly-analysis/instruction-set-architecture] The demands of high-speed digital signal processing have pushed in the opposite direction—forcing instructions to be implemented in a particular way.
[src:disassembly-analysis/instruction-set-architecture] For example, to perform digital filters fast enough, the MAC instruction in a typical digital signal processor (DSP) must use a kind of Harvard architecture that can fetch an instruction and two data words simultaneously, and it requires a single-cycle multiply–accumulate multiplier.
[src:disassembly-analysis/interactive-disassembler] The **Interactive Disassembler** (**IDA**) is a disassembler for computer software which generates assembly language source code from machine-executable code.
[src:disassembly-analysis/interactive-disassembler] It supports a variety of executable formats for different processors and operating systems.
[src:disassembly-analysis/interactive-disassembler] It can also be used as a debugger for Windows PE, Mac OS X Mach-O, and Linux ELF executables.
[src:disassembly-analysis/interactive-disassembler] A decompiler plug-in, which generates a high level, C source code-like representation of the analysed program, is available at extra cost.
[src:disassembly-analysis/interactive-disassembler] IDA is used widely in software reverse engineering, including for malware analysis and software vulnerability research.
[src:disassembly-analysis/interactive-disassembler] IDA's decompiler is one of the most popular and widely used decompilation frameworks, and IDA has been called the "de-facto industry standard" for program disassembly and static binary analysis.
[src:disassembly-analysis/interactive-disassembler] Ilfak Guilfanov began working on IDA in 1990, and initially distributed it as a shareware application.
[src:disassembly-analysis/interactive-disassembler] In 1996, the Belgian company DataRescue took over the development of IDA and began to sell it as a commercial product, under the name IDA Pro.
[src:disassembly-analysis/interactive-disassembler] Initial versions of IDA did not have a graphical user interface (GUI), and ran as an extended DOS, OS/2, or Windows console application.
[src:disassembly-analysis/interactive-disassembler] In 1999, DataRescue released the first version of IDA Pro with a GUI, IDA Pro 4.0.
[src:disassembly-analysis/interactive-disassembler] In 2005, Guilfanov founded Hex-Rays to pursue the development of the Hex-Rays Decompiler IDA extension.
[src:disassembly-analysis/interactive-disassembler] In January 2008, Hex-Rays assumed the development and support of DataRescue's IDA Pro.
[src:disassembly-analysis/interactive-disassembler] In 2022, Hex-Rays was acquired by a group of investors led by Smartfin, a European venture capital and private equity investor.
[src:disassembly-analysis/interactive-disassembler] Co-investors in the acquisition included the Belgian public holding company The Federal Holding & Investment Company (SFPIM), and the Walloon public investment firm Regional Investment Company of Wallonia (SRIW).
[src:disassembly-analysis/interactive-disassembler] IDA disassembles a compiled program back into an assembly language representation.
[src:disassembly-analysis/interactive-disassembler] However, the nature of disassembly precludes total accuracy, and a great deal of human intervention is necessarily required; IDA has interactive functionality to aid in improving the disassembly.
[src:disassembly-analysis/interactive-disassembler] A typical IDA user will begin with an automatically generated disassembly listing and then convert sections from code to data and vice versa, rename, annotate, and otherwise add information to the listing, until its functionality becomes clear.
[src:disassembly-analysis/interactive-disassembler] "IDC scripts" make it possible to extend the operation of the disassembler.
[src:disassembly-analysis/interactive-disassembler] Some helpful scripts are provided, which can serve as the basis for user written scripts.
[src:disassembly-analysis/interactive-disassembler] Most frequently scripts are used for extra modification of the generated code.
[src:disassembly-analysis/interactive-disassembler] For example, external symbol tables can be loaded, thereby using the function names of the original source code.
[src:disassembly-analysis/interactive-disassembler] Users have created plugins that allow other common scripting languages to be used instead of, or in addition to, IDC.
[src:disassembly-analysis/interactive-disassembler] IdaRUB supports Ruby and IDAPython adds support for Python.
[src:disassembly-analysis/interactive-disassembler] As of version 5.4, IDAPython (dependent on Python 2.5) comes preinstalled with IDA Pro.
[src:disassembly-analysis/interactive-disassembler] The latest full version of IDA Pro is available via paid annual subscription (version 9.0sp1 as of December 2024), while a less capable version (limited to x86), named IDA Free, is available for download free of cost.
[src:disassembly-analysis/interactive-disassembler] IDA Pro's logo is a cropped image of Françoise d'Aubigné, Marquise de Maintenon.
[src:disassembly-analysis/interactive-disassembler] The logo image is similar to a miniature painting of Françoise d'Aubigné attested to a painter in the circle of Pierre Mignard.
[src:disassembly-analysis/interactive-disassembler] The original greyscale version of the logo was introduced in September 1999, with the release of IDA 4.0.
[src:disassembly-analysis/interactive-disassembler] Ilfak Guilfanov has stated that the logo is not a depiction of Saint Ida of Louvain.
[src:disassembly-analysis/opcode] In computing, an **opcode** (abbreviated from **operation code**) is an enumerated value that specifies the operation to be performed.
[src:disassembly-analysis/opcode] Opcodes are employed in hardware devices such as arithmetic logic units (ALUs), central processing units (CPUs), and software instruction sets.
[src:disassembly-analysis/opcode] In ALUs, the opcode is directly applied to circuitry via an input signal bus.
[src:disassembly-analysis/opcode] In contrast, in CPUs, the opcode is the portion of a machine language instruction that specifies the operation to be performed.
[src:disassembly-analysis/opcode] Opcodes are found in the machine language instructions of CPUs as well as in some abstract computing machines.
[src:disassembly-analysis/opcode] In CPUs, an opcode may be referred to as an **instruction machine code**, **instruction code**, **instruction syllable**, **instruction parcel,** or **opstring**.
[src:disassembly-analysis/opcode] For any particular processor (which may be a general CPU or a more specialized processing unit), the opcodes are defined by the processor's instruction set architecture (ISA).
[src:disassembly-analysis/opcode] They can be described using an opcode table.
[src:disassembly-analysis/opcode] The types of operations may include arithmetic, data copying, logical operations, program control, and special instructions (e.g., CPUID).
[src:disassembly-analysis/opcode] In addition to the opcode, many instructions specify the data (known as operands) the operation will act upon, although some instructions may have implicit operands or none.
[src:disassembly-analysis/opcode] Some instruction sets have nearly uniform fields for opcode and operand specifiers, whereas others (e.g., x86 architecture) have a less uniform, variable-length structure.
[src:disassembly-analysis/opcode] Instruction sets can be extended through opcode prefixes, which add a subset of new instructions made up of existing opcodes following reserved byte sequences.
[src:disassembly-analysis/opcode] This table shows opcodes of a simple 8-bit microprocessor, the Intel 8008 from 1972.
[src:disassembly-analysis/opcode] Each is shown as a binary pattern of ones and zeros in the **Opcode** column.
[src:disassembly-analysis/opcode] Up to two additional fields may be embedded into the opcode.
[src:disassembly-analysis/opcode] Some 3-bit fields are labeled DDD, SSS, CC, and ALU.
[src:disassembly-analysis/opcode] The SSS (source) and DDD (destination) fields specify one of the eight possible 8008 registers or memory: A, B, C, D, E, H, L, or M.
[src:disassembly-analysis/opcode] CC specifies one of eight result conditions that will activate certain JMP, CAL, and RET instructions.
[src:disassembly-analysis/opcode] ALU specifies one of a possible eight arithmetic logic unit functions to be performed during an instruction, specifically, add, add with carry, subtract, subtract with borrow, logical AND, logical XOR, logical OR, and compare.
[src:disassembly-analysis/opcode] The **X** in some fields means that either a 1 or 0 can be inserted with no effect.
[src:disassembly-analysis/opcode] The fixed ones and zeros are combined with the parameter fields to build the 8-bit opcode.
[src:disassembly-analysis/opcode] Additionally, the full instruction might require one or two additional bytes of operands.
[src:disassembly-analysis/opcode] These are shown in the second major column of the table, labeled **Operands**.
[src:disassembly-analysis/opcode] If no operands are required, the column is filled with a dash (—).
[src:disassembly-analysis/opcode] Since the ones and zeros are difficult to remember, the **Mnemonic** column shows a short, easy to remember letter code that an assembly language programmer may use to invoke the required opcode.
[src:disassembly-analysis/opcode] The **Description** column shows the function performed by the microprocessor when it encounters a specific opcode.
[src:disassembly-analysis/opcode] Opcodes can be found in bytecodes and other representations intended for execution by software interpreters.
[src:disassembly-analysis/opcode] These often employ slightly higher-level data types and operations than those found in hardware opcodes but are nevertheless constructed along similar lines.
[src:disassembly-analysis/opcode] Examples include the byte code found in Java class files, which are interpreted by Java virtual machines, the byte code used in GNU Emacs for compiled Lisp code, and NET Common Intermediate Language.
